node.text:
This meeting went better than I could have expected. Lark may sound mean in these clips, but the sounds she is making are just her letting Fig know she’s a little uncomfortable and setting some boundaries. After about 30 minutes they spent the rest of the day napping under the couch together. It’s a huge sign of trust to sleep so close to one another! 
-
Can you spot one major difference between them? Notice how much larger Fig is and how much fuller his coat is than hers? Fur farm foxes have been bred to be significantly larger than wild North American foxes.
#larkthefox

node.text: Yesterday Herbal made it through his surgery, but around 9pm his heart stopped. The vets are not exactly sure why he crashed so suddenly, especially after it had been serval hours since he had woken from surgery. My heart aches since he was truly my little buddy. I thought it would be nice to share with all of you the first day I brought him home almost three years ago.

node.text:
After weeks of not being able to find a vet specialized enough to care for Herbal I resorted to making a story begging for help. I was lucky enough to catch the eye of a wonderful vet in Atlanta, Jessica, who was kind enough to walk me through what I needed and pointed me to the Univerity Of Florida Small Mammal Hosptial, where Herbal has been receiving intensive care since Monday. 
-
The staff at UF was able to get him stable, eating, and after a CT scan they were finally able to identify the cause of his issues.
-
Dental disease can be genetic or due to improper care. In Herbal’s case it’s both. Herbal came to me as a neglect case and was fed exclusively hamster food by his previous owner. This poor diet has lead him to where he is now. Chinchilla’s diet needs to be 80% hay to help keep their teeth and digestive tract healthy. Even two years of proper diet and care was not enough to revert the damage that was done by his previous diet. 
-
When adopting an animal please make sure to do proper research on the care that animal requires to be their healthiest. Chinchillas have a lifespan of around 20 years, Herbal is only 3 and will now live with this condition the rest of his life.

node.text:
“Where’s Elmwood Been?”
-
Lately whenever I post I get quite a few comments asking about Elmwood and why he hasn’t been popping up as frequently. So I thought I’d deep dive into an explanation. 
-
When I moved into our new property last fall I asked my brother to move in with myself and the animals, since the “new house” was going to be a huge project and needed a lot of renovations. Unfortunately, since Elmwood was a kit he’s been terrified of my brother. He isn’t like this with any other person, and it was strange seeing such a small baby with no hesitation around strangers being stand offish with only one person for no apparent reasoning.
-
Since moving Elmwood spends most of his time outdoors and tends to prefer being as far away from our living spaces as possible to avoid running into Jake. When he is indoors he’s usually under the couch or my bed unless he’s busy raiding the kitchen cabinets. 
-
Long story short, Elmwood has become somewhat of a recluse during indoor group time. We’ve been working on socialization with Jake, but he hasn’t made much progress and with Jake moving out in a few months I’ve wondered if it’s worth the stress of forcing exposure even if it is positively reinforced.
-
Our large two acre fox yard is still underway and once that’s complete I’ll be sure to share his new outdoor shenanigans! In the meantime, know that he’s well and just being a bit of a hermit.

node.text:
#ad When Fig broke his leg we got so many comments asking if we had cameras in the room to watch the foxes. At the time we did not, but Google was kind enough to send us their new battery-powered #NestCam and #NestDoorbell with intelligent alerts to help me keep an eye on the animals even when I’m not home.
•
The Nest Cam works both indoors and outdoors and the Nest Doorbell alerts us for the things that matter most; like if a package or family member arrives! This is so helpful because the camera can recognize people who may be on the property when I’m not there and the foxes are in their enclosures outdoors. I can’t wait to put these to use!
•
We’re excited to see all the silly things our animals get into at home. Make sure to share your own pet videos with #CaughtOnNestCam for a chance to be featured on @MadeByGoogle
